History and Fun Facts
The Gadsden County Country Club (currently known as the Golf Club of 
		Quincy) opened for business in the Spring of 1968. It took 3 years of 
		hard work to prepare for this opening. Some of the people involved with 
		this effort included: George Bates, Ernest Bietenholz, John Clark, 
		Arthur Corry, Dick D'Alemberte, Bill Dodson, Ben Duncan, Sr., Joe Duys, 
		Howard Fletcher, Carl Fowler, Jack Harnett, Pat Higdon, George E. 
		Johnson, W.D. Lines, Bill Malone, Lamar Munroe, Jr., Ralph Perkins,  
		Bob Smith, John Allen Smith, Joe Spitz, Pat Suber, Forrest Taylor, Earl 
		Willis and many others.
The golf course was designed by Joe Lee.
The first golf professional was Ronnie Laffoon 
		and his assistants were Johnnie Milan and Carl Rudio.
The first hole-in-one was made by Alex 
		McMillan.
Image from Gadsden County Times, April 25, 1968, Gadsden Country Club 
	Grand Opening

Golf Club Of Quincy
NOTICE:
Daily lunch specials are available for dine in or take out. Call 850-627-9631 
	for the daily menu and to order for pick up.
The Golf Club of Quincy is located 3.5 north of Quincy, Florida on Hwy 268 just 30 minutes northwest of Florida's capital city. The scenic, quiet, 18-hole, Par 73, 6,640 yard golf course is a unique Joe Lee design featuring unusual elevation changes for a Florida layout.
The semi-private club offers affordable club memberships.
In addition to golf, the Golf Club of Quincy offers a restaurant, bar and grill, meeting rooms, banquet facilities, exercise room, driving range, tennis courts and swimming pool.
Welcome to Our Club
Our clubhouse is a second home to our members, and guests are always welcome!
Enjoy full dinning during weekday lunches and Friday night dinners.
Our lunch menu includes a full soup and salad bar with a different lunch special each weekday. Or, pull up a chair, order from our grille menu and enjoy the ballgame at our bar and grille.
